B.MN=new A.Z(B.p,[1,1,"Awakening","M","Moment",!1,"What is the first honest word that comes to mind when you ask yourself: how am I, really?","You are not broken. You are beginning.","Pennebaker's research shows the first unedited response is the most diagnostically accurate. Don't think. Just write."],t.R)
B.Me=new A.Z(B.p,[2,1,"Awakening","I","Identify",!1,"Look at the Feelings Wheel. Which word feels closest to what you carry right now? Where in your body do you feel it?","Naming it is the first act of freedom.","Affect labeling \u2014 putting a word to a feeling \u2014 reduces amygdala activity and increases prefrontal engagement. You are literally calming your brain by naming what you feel."],t.R)
B.Ml=new A.Z(B.p,[3,1,"Awakening","M","Moment",!1,"What does your mind keep returning to today? Not what you think it should. What it actually keeps returning to.","The answer is already in you.","Rumination tracking is the first diagnostic tool in CBT. Awareness of recurring thoughts is the precondition for change."],t.R)
B.LS=new A.Z(B.p,[4,1,"Awakening","I","Identify",!1,"Name one emotion you rarely allow yourself to feel. What would happen if you let it exist, just for a moment?","Suppressed emotions do not disappear. They wait.","Emotional suppression research (Gross & Levenson, 1993) shows unexpressed emotions consume more cognitive resources than expressed ones."],t.R)
B.ME=new A.Z(B.p,[5,1,"Awakening","M","Moment",!1,"What are you pretending is fine right now? Write it without softening it.","Honesty, even on paper, changes something.","Authenticity-based writing prompts produce stronger therapeutic outcomes than vague reflection. The specificity is the medicine."],t.R)
B.LH=new A.Z(B.p,[6,1,"Awakening","R","Reframe",!0,"Think of something that felt like a failure recently. Write it down. Now write three things that experience may have been trying to teach you.","What if it was not a failure at all?","Dedicated reframe days every 6th day activate cognitive flexibility and interrupt rumination cycles \u2014 Beck's cognitive reframing model."],t.R)
B.Mt=new A.Z(B.p,[7,1,"Awakening","I","Identify",!1,"What emotion do you most frequently mask in front of others? What would change if people knew?","The mask costs more than you think.","Chronic emotional concealment is linked to increased anxiety and reduced relationship quality. Surface acting has a measurable physiological cost."],t.R)
B.Mr=new A.Z(B.p,[8,1,"Awakening","M","Moment",!1,"Describe the last time you felt fully at peace. What was present? What was absent?","Peace leaves clues.","Contrast-based reflection reveals personal wellbeing conditions that are invisible when life is viewed as continuous."],t.R)
B.My=new A.Z(B.p,[9,1,"Awakening","I","Identify",!1,"What does stress feel like in your body right now? Be as specific and physical as possible.","The body knows before the mind admits.","Somatic awareness \u2014 reading internal physical states \u2014 is strongly correlated with emotional intelligence and regulation capacity."],t.R)
B.Mm=new A.Z(B.p,[10,1,"Awakening","M","Moment",!1,"What story are you telling yourself about your life? Is it accurate, or is it a very old story that no longer fits?","Stories can be rewritten.","Narrative identity theory (McAdams) shows the stories we construct about ourselves directly shape behavior, motivation, and emotional health."],t.R)
B.MI=new A.Z(B.p,[11,1,"Awakening","I","Identify",!1,"What are you most afraid people would see if they truly knew you?","The things we hide have the most to teach us.","Shame resilience research (Bren\xe9 Brown) shows naming feared perceptions is the first step toward dismantling their power."],t.R)
B.LY=new A.Z(B.p,[12,1,"Awakening","R","Reframe",!0,"Write about something you are worried about. Now write it again as if you are telling the story to yourself five years from now. What changes?","Time is the most powerful reframe.","Temporal distancing (Kross & Ayduk) is one of the most effective reframing techniques \u2014 mental time travel reduces emotional intensity of current stressors."],t.R)
B.MH=new A.Z(B.p,[13,1,"Awakening","M","Moment",!1,"What does your inner voice most often say to you? If that voice belonged to someone else, who would it be?","You can change who narrates your life.","Inner critic identification is a core technique in Internal Family Systems therapy. Naming the voice externalizes it and reduces its authority."],t.R)
B.LU=new A.Z(B.p,[14,1,"Awakening","I","Identify",!1,"What feeling have you been avoiding for weeks, months, maybe years? What would it cost to finally name it here?","Avoidance is not the same as peace.","Emotional avoidance is the single most common maintaining factor across anxiety disorders \u2014 Hayes, Acceptance and Commitment Therapy."],t.R)
B.LZ=new A.Z(B.p,[15,1,"Awakening","M","Moment",!1,"Where do you feel most like yourself? Where do you feel least like yourself? What is different between those two places?","The gap is worth studying.","Authentic self-concept research shows environments affecting authenticity are strong predictors of wellbeing and identity stability."],t.R)
B.Mf=new A.Z(B.p,[16,1,"Awakening","I","Identify",!1,"What belief about yourself have you held for a long time \u2014 about who you are, what you deserve, what you are capable of? Where did it come from?","Not all beliefs were chosen.","Core belief identification is the foundational step in cognitive restructuring. Beliefs formed in childhood disproportionately shape adult emotional responses."],t.R)
B.MO=new A.Z(B.p,[17,1,"Awakening","M","Moment",!1,"What are you saying you will deal with later? What is the honest reason it keeps getting delayed?","Later is a feeling, not a time.","Procrastination research consistently links avoidance to emotional discomfort rather than poor time management \u2014 Fuschia Sirois, 2014."],t.R)
B.MP=new A.Z(B.p,[18,1,"Awakening","R","Reframe",!0,"Look back at the past 18 days. What is one thing you have noticed about yourself that you did not fully see before? What does that awareness change?","Seeing clearly is its own kind of courage.","End-of-phase reflection anchors learning and creates psychological closure \u2014 a key mechanism in progressive journaling programs."],t.R)
B.Lz=new A.Z(B.p,[19,2,"Excavation","R","Reflect",!1,"Think of an emotion you experienced in childhood that you were taught \u2014 directly or indirectly \u2014 was not acceptable. How does that teaching still live in you today?","Old rules can be unlearned.","Childhood emotional socialization research (Gottman) shows early messages about emotional acceptability become internalized rules that govern adult expression."],t.R)
B.MC=new A.Z(B.p,[20,2,"Excavation","R","Reflect",!1,"Who in your life do you feel most emotionally safe with? What specifically makes that safety possible?","Safety is not luck. It is a condition. You can create more of it.","Attachment theory identifies felt safety as the prerequisite for authentic emotional expression."],t.R)
B.MA=new A.Z(B.p,[21,2,"Excavation","R","Reflect",!1,"What do you most need to hear from someone right now \u2014 but haven't? Write yourself the message you have been waiting for.","You already know what you need.","Self-compassionate letter-writing is one of the most evidence-backed interventions in Kristin Neff's self-compassion framework."],t.R)
B.Ms=new A.Z(B.p,[22,2,"Excavation","R","Reflect",!1,"What are the conditions under which you feel most like a failure? What belief system does that feeling rest on?","The belief is not the fact.","Failure scripts are often automatic cognitive schemas. Identifying the conditions is more useful than analyzing the feeling itself."],t.R)
B.M8=new A.Z(B.p,[23,2,"Excavation","R","Reflect",!1,"What relationship in your life \u2014 past or present \u2014 has most shaped how you see yourself? In what specific ways?","Knowing the source changes the power it has.","Relational self-concept theory shows interpersonal experiences directly construct the internal working models we use to interpret ourselves."],t.R)
B.Ma=new A.Z(B.p,[24,2,"Excavation","R","Reframe",!0,"Write about something you genuinely resent. Now write it again from the perspective of what the resentment is protecting you from feeling.","Resentment is always protecting something underneath.","Resentment is a secondary emotion \u2014 it is almost always protecting a primary wound of hurt, fear, or grief. Adapted from Emotion-Focused Therapy (Greenberg)."],t.R)
B.M2=new A.Z(B.p,[25,2,"Excavation","R","Reflect",!1,'What does "enough" look like for you \u2014 in work, in relationships, in yourself? Where did your definition of enough come from?',"You get to choose what enough means.",'Research on perfectionism (Hewitt & Flett) shows the definition of "enough" is almost always externally derived rather than internally chosen.'],t.R)
B.Mx=new A.Z(B.p,[26,2,"Excavation","R","Reflect",!1,"What is a version of yourself you have been trying to leave behind? What parts of that version do you still carry?","Integration is more honest than rejection.","Identity continuity research shows the attempt to fully reject a former self creates internal fragmentation. Integration is the healthier path."],t.R)
B.Ly=new A.Z(B.p,[27,2,"Excavation","R","Reflect",!1,"When was the last time you felt genuinely proud of yourself \u2014 not for what you achieved, but for who you were in a moment?","Character-based pride lasts longer than achievement-based pride.","Character-based pride (Tracy & Robins, 2007) is a stronger predictor of stable self-esteem than achievement-based pride."],t.R)
B.MM=new A.Z(B.p,[28,2,"Excavation","R","Reflect",!1,"What emotion do you find hardest to receive from others \u2014 love, admiration, disappointment, anger? What does that difficulty reveal?","What we cannot receive in others, we often cannot give ourselves.","Difficulty receiving certain emotions from others often mirrors difficulty allowing those emotions in oneself \u2014 a key insight from relational psychotherapy."],t.R)
B.Lx=new A.Z(B.p,[29,2,"Excavation","R","Reflect",!1,"Write about a time you betrayed your own values. Not a mistake \u2014 a moment when you knew what was right and didn't do it. What happened inside you?","Naming it here begins the repair.","Moral injury research shows self-betrayal events are among the most persistent sources of shame and are frequently avoided in self-reflection."],t.R)
B.Mz=new A.Z(B.p,[30,2,"Excavation","R","Reframe",!0,"Write about something you feel guilty about. Now ask: is this guilt appropriate \u2014 did you genuinely cause harm \u2014 or is it a feeling you were taught to carry that doesn't actually belong to you?","Not every weight you carry belongs to you.","Distinguishing authentic guilt from internalized shame is a core intervention in schema therapy and trauma-informed approaches."],t.R)
B.Mk=new A.Z(B.p,[31,2,"Excavation","R","Reflect",!1,"What need do you most consistently put last? What would your life look like if you moved it to first for one week?","Your needs are not an inconvenience.","Self-Determination Theory (Deci & Ryan) shows chronic needs suppression is a primary driver of emotional dysregulation."],t.R)
B.LC=new A.Z(B.p,[32,2,"Excavation","R","Reflect",!1,"Think about a time you felt deeply misunderstood. What were you actually trying to communicate? What got lost?","Being misunderstood does not make you wrong.","The gap between intended meaning and received meaning is the primary source of relational distress."],t.R)
B.M5=new A.Z(B.p,[33,2,"Excavation","R","Reflect",!1,'What are you grieving right now \u2014 even if what you lost doesn\'t seem "big enough" to grieve?',"All grief counts. All of it.","Ambiguous loss theory (Pauline Boss) shows we carry unacknowledged grief about changes and transitions that don't qualify for formal mourning \u2014 and this grief affects us deeply regardless."],t.R)
B.LE=new A.Z(B.p,[34,2,"Excavation","R","Reflect",!1,"What would you do differently in your life if you were certain you wouldn't be judged for it?","The life you want and the life you perform are not the same thing.","Fear of Negative Evaluation is the most common hidden factor in life decisions that do not align with authentic values."],t.R)
B.Lu=new A.Z(B.p,[35,2,"Excavation","R","Reflect",!1,"What has this phase of your life been asking you to learn? Not what you wish it were teaching you \u2014 what it is actually teaching you.","The lesson and the pain are not the same thing. But they often arrive together.","Post-traumatic growth research (Tedeschi & Calhoun) shows making meaning from difficult periods is the distinguishing factor in resilience."],t.R)
B.Mg=new A.Z(B.p,[36,2,"Excavation","R","Reframe",!0,"Look back at Phase 2. What underground truth has surfaced that you hadn't fully acknowledged before? What would change if you let yourself fully believe it?","What you have excavated does not go back underground.","End-of-phase integration prompts consolidate learning through narrative synthesis \u2014 weaving insights into a coherent self-story."],t.R)
B.LF=new A.Z(B.p,[37,3,"The Turn","R","Reframe",!1,'Take a belief you hold about what you are "not good at." Write the evidence that supports this belief. Now write the evidence that contradicts it. Which list was harder to write?',"The contradictory evidence is always there. You just don't usually look for it.","Confirmation bias leads us to weight evidence that confirms existing beliefs more heavily. Deliberately constructing the contradictory case weakens the belief's grip."],t.R)
B.Mo=new A.Z(B.p,[38,3,"The Turn","R","Reframe",!1,"Think of someone who frustrates or angers you. Write one paragraph from their perspective \u2014 not to excuse their behavior, but to genuinely understand what drives it.","Understanding is not the same as agreeing.","Perspective-taking reduces interpersonal conflict and increases empathy without requiring agreement."],t.R)
B.Mw=new A.Z(B.p,[39,3,"The Turn","R","Reframe",!1,'What is something you have been calling a "problem" that might more accurately be called a "sign"? What might it be pointing toward?',"Problems are often misdirected signals.","Reframing obstacles as information rather than opposition is a key cognitive shift in solution-focused therapy."],t.R)
B.LK=new A.Z(B.p,[40,3,"The Turn","R","Reframe",!1,"Write about a version of your future self that you find hard to believe in. What specific beliefs are making that future feel impossible? Are those beliefs facts or interpretations?","The future self is already there. The beliefs are what block the view.","Future self-continuity research (Hershfield) shows psychological distance from our future selves is the primary driver of self-defeating present behavior."],t.R)
B.MR=new A.Z(B.p,[41,3,"The Turn","R","Reframe",!1,"What is something that happened to you that, at the time, felt like the worst possible outcome \u2014 but that you can now see differently?","Perspective is a gift time gives slowly.","Retrospective reappraisal is one of the primary mechanisms through which adversity produces personal transformation."],t.R)
B.LT=new A.Z(B.p,[42,3,"The Turn","R","Reframe",!0,"Choose your most persistent negative self-belief. Write a defense of that belief. Now write the cross-examination \u2014 every question that challenges its validity.","The belief cannot survive honest cross-examination.","Socratic questioning from CBT uses systematic inquiry rather than direct challenge to destabilize rigid negative beliefs."],t.R)
B.LN=new A.Z(B.p,[43,3,"The Turn","R","Reframe",!1,"What are you currently in conflict about \u2014 with someone else or within yourself? Write the version where both sides are valid. What does that version reveal?","Two things can be true at the same time.","Dialectical thinking \u2014 holding two contradictory truths simultaneously \u2014 is the foundation of DBT and produces more nuanced, less reactive responses."],t.R)
B.LR=new A.Z(B.p,[44,3,"The Turn","R","Reframe",!1,"What story do you tell about your past that keeps you feeling stuck? Write it. Now write the same story, told by a version of you who has completely healed from it.","You are allowed to tell a different story.","Narrative therapy (White & Epston) shows re-authoring one's personal story from a healed perspective creates emotional distance and new possibility."],t.R)
B.Mp=new A.Z(B.p,[45,3,"The Turn","R","Reframe",!1,"What is something about your character that you have always seen as a weakness? Write three ways that same quality could be, or has been, a strength.","The same quality can be a wound or a weapon, depending on how you hold it.","Strength reframing is a core technique in positive psychology interventions."],t.R)
B.MD=new A.Z(B.p,[46,3,"The Turn","R","Reframe",!1,"What would you think of a close friend who was going through exactly what you are going through right now? Write the advice you would give them \u2014 then notice whether you allow yourself to receive the same advice.","You deserve the same compassion you give freely to others.","Self-compassion research (Neff, 2003) consistently shows the gap between how we treat friends in difficulty and how we treat ourselves is a primary driver of shame."],t.R)
B.MG=new A.Z(B.p,[47,3,"The Turn","R","Reframe",!1,"What is a rule you have been living by \u2014 about how you should behave, what you must achieve, what you cannot show \u2014 that you never consciously chose? Where did this rule come from?","Rules you did not choose can be returned.","Unconscious life rules (schema therapy's conditional assumptions) govern behavior automatically until identified and consciously evaluated."],t.R)
B.LJ=new A.Z(B.p,[48,3,"The Turn","R","Reframe",!0,"Write about something in your life that feels permanent and fixed. Now ask: what would have to change for this to shift? Is that change possible? What is the smallest possible first step?","Fixed is a feeling, not a fact.","Fixed versus growth mindset research (Dweck) shows the belief in changeability \u2014 not actual ability \u2014 is the strongest predictor of effort and resilience."],t.R)
B.Lt=new A.Z(B.p,[49,3,"The Turn","R","Reframe",!1,"What does failure mean to you? Write your definition. Now write the definition that a person who is not afraid of failure would use instead.","Fear of failure lives in the definition, not the outcome.","Fear of failure research shows the definition of failure \u2014 not the outcome itself \u2014 determines whether challenge is approached or avoided."],t.R)
B.Mu=new A.Z(B.p,[50,3,"The Turn","R","Reframe",!1,"What are you currently carrying that belongs to someone else \u2014 someone else's expectations, fears, pain, or unfinished emotional business?","You are allowed to hand it back.","Differentiation of self (Bowen family systems theory) identifies the ability to distinguish one's own emotional material from absorbed family material as a key marker of emotional maturity."],t.R)
B.LW=new A.Z(B.p,[51,3,"The Turn","R","Reframe",!1,'What is one area of your life where you are waiting for permission \u2014 from someone else, from circumstances, from a version of yourself that feels "ready"? What if you stopped waiting?',"Ready is a myth. Begin anyway.","Internal locus of control \u2014 the belief that one has agency over outcomes \u2014 is one of the most robust predictors of psychological wellbeing."],t.R)
B.LX=new A.Z(B.p,[52,3,"The Turn","R","Reframe",!1,"Think about the person you are becoming. Write a letter from that future version of you to who you are right now. What do they want you to know?","Your future self is rooting for you.","Future self-visualization activates the brain's default mode network in ways that create genuine motivational scaffolding."],t.R)
B.LI=new A.Z(B.p,[53,3,"The Turn","R","Reframe",!1,"What is the most important thing Phase 3 has shifted in how you see yourself or your life? Write it as clearly and specifically as possible.","A shift in perception is a shift in reality.","Explicit insight articulation \u2014 writing out reframes in precise language \u2014 is necessary to consolidate new cognitive pathways."],t.R)
B.LB=new A.Z(B.p,[54,3,"The Turn","R","Reframe",!0,"What does a life guided by your values rather than your fears look like? Describe it in specific, sensory detail. Then write: what is one thing stopping you from living more of that life right now?","Values-based living is a daily decision, not a destination.","Values-based action combined with barrier identification is the most effective combination for initiating lasting behavior change \u2014 ACT."],t.R)
B.MS=new A.Z(B.p,[55,4,"Pattern Work","O","Observe",!1,"What is the emotional pattern you repeat most reliably in relationships? Describe it as precisely as you can.","Seeing the pattern is already different from being inside it.","Repetition compulsion shows unresolved emotional patterns actively seek re-enactment until consciously recognized and interrupted."],t.R)
B.ML=new A.Z(B.p,[56,4,"Pattern Work","O","Observe",!1,"What type of situation consistently makes you feel small, dismissed, or unseen? What is the common thread across all of those situations?","The thread is the teacher.","Common denominator analysis \u2014 finding the thread that connects triggers \u2014 reveals the underlying schema driving the response."],t.R)
B.LL=new A.Z(B.p,[57,4,"Pattern Work","O","Observe",!1,"Look back at your first 56 days of entries. What word, theme, or feeling has appeared most frequently? What does its frequency tell you?","Patterns become visible only when you look across time.","Longitudinal self-reflection data reveals patterns that in-the-moment reflection cannot access."],t.R)
B.Lv=new A.Z(B.p,[58,4,"Pattern Work","O","Observe",!1,"What is your habitual response when you feel threatened \u2014 do you fight, flee, freeze, or fawn? What does that response cost you?","The response made sense once. It may not still.","Polyvagal theory identifies threat response patterns as automatic nervous system responses. Awareness of the pattern is the precondition for choosing differently."],t.R)
B.MQ=new A.Z(B.p,[59,4,"Pattern Work","O","Observe",!1,"When do you most reliably abandon your own needs to take care of someone else's? What is happening inside you in those moments?","Caring for others and abandoning yourself are not the same thing.","Fawning and self-abandonment patterns are highly prevalent in individuals with anxious attachment histories."],t.R)
B.M0=new A.Z(B.p,[60,4,"Pattern Work","O","Reframe",!0,"Identify your most self-limiting pattern. If this pattern were a strategy your younger self developed to stay safe, what was it protecting? Can you feel compassion for that version of you?","The pattern was protection once. You are safe enough now to choose differently.","Understanding self-limiting patterns as formerly adaptive strategies reduces self-criticism while enabling change \u2014 schema therapy."],t.R)
B.M1=new A.Z(B.p,[61,4,"Pattern Work","O","Observe",!1,"What patterns do you see in what makes you genuinely happy? Not what you think should make you happy \u2014 what actually, consistently does?","Sustainable happiness has a pattern. Find yours.","Most people have poor insight into their own sources of sustainable happiness because hedonic adaptation makes pleasure invisible when it becomes consistent."],t.R)
B.MT=new A.Z(B.p,[62,4,"Pattern Work","O","Observe",!1,"When do you most consistently feel disconnected from yourself \u2014 from your values, your body, your sense of who you are? What are the conditions?","Disconnection has conditions. Conditions can be changed.","Mapping the conditions of self-disconnection enables targeted intervention."],t.R)
B.M6=new A.Z(B.p,[63,4,"Pattern Work","O","Observe",!1,"What is your pattern around asking for help? Do you ask too readily, too rarely, or selectively? What drives the pattern?","Asking for help is not weakness. It is accurate self-knowledge.","Help-seeking behavior patterns are deeply linked to attachment style and early experiences of having needs met or dismissed."],t.R)
B.Mn=new A.Z(B.p,[64,4,"Pattern Work","O","Observe",!1,"What is the recurring thought that appears most reliably when you lie awake at night or first wake in the morning? What does its persistence reveal?","The 3am thought is trying to tell you something.","Pre-sleep cognitions are among the most diagnostically accurate indicators of chronic underlying anxiety themes \u2014 they bypass the cognitive filtering of the waking state."],t.R)
B.Mh=new A.Z(B.p,[65,4,"Pattern Work","O","Observe",!1,"What patterns do you see in who you choose to spend time with? What unmet need does your social circle reflect?","Your environment is not neutral. It reflects you \u2014 and shapes you.","Social environment selection is heavily influenced by attachment patterns and self-concept."],t.R)
B.MB=new A.Z(B.p,[66,4,"Pattern Work","O","Reframe",!0,"Choose one pattern you are ready to interrupt. Write in specific detail: what does the pattern look like, what triggers it, and what one different response could you practice next time it appears?","Interrupting a pattern once is the proof it can be interrupted.","Habit interruption research shows plans made with specific situational context are dramatically more effective than general behavioral intentions \u2014 Gollwitzer, 1999."],t.R)
B.LQ=new A.Z(B.p,[67,4,"Pattern Work","O","Observe",!1,"When you are at your worst \u2014 most reactive, most shut down, most unkind to yourself \u2014 what are the conditions? How early in that process can you now detect it?","Early detection changes everything.","Early detection of emotional dysregulation onset is one of the most trainable skills in DBT and dramatically improves the success rate of interruption."],t.R)
B.LO=new A.Z(B.p,[68,4,"Pattern Work","O","Observe",!1,"What is the pattern in how you handle endings \u2014 of relationships, projects, phases of life? What emotion most consistently accompanies endings for you?","How you end things says something about how you hold them.","Ending behavior patterns reveal core attachment style and grief processing capacity."],t.R)
B.LP=new A.Z(B.p,[69,4,"Pattern Work","O","Observe",!1,"What decisions have you made in the last year that, in hindsight, were driven more by fear than by genuine desire? What pattern do you see?","Fear-based decisions are recognizable in hindsight. With practice, they become recognizable in real time.","Fear-based decision making is an automatic process until made explicit. Awareness of the fear/desire distinction is a major outcome of successful psychological work."],t.R)
B.Mv=new A.Z(B.p,[70,4,"Pattern Work","O","Observe",!1,"What is the most important pattern you have discovered about yourself in the last 70 days? Not the most comfortable \u2014 the most important.","The most important insight is always the one that was hardest to see.","Integration prompts at key milestones produce significantly stronger retention of insights than open-ended reflection alone."],t.R)
B.LV=new A.Z(B.p,[71,4,"Pattern Work","O","Observe",!1,"What pattern in yourself are you most proud of having recognized? Not changed yet \u2014 simply seen clearly?","Recognition without judgment is its own form of growth.","Recognition-without-change affirmations prevent the common trap of self-punishment for patterns not yet altered, which increases shame and reduces motivation to change."],t.R)
B.Mq=new A.Z(B.p,[72,4,"Pattern Work","O","Reframe",!0,"Look at the patterns you have mapped in Phase 4. Choose one you are committing to work on going forward. Write what that will look like in practice \u2014 not in general terms, but in the specific situations where it appears.","A commitment made in writing is a commitment made twice.","Implementation intentions \u2014 plans with specific situational context \u2014 are dramatically more effective than general behavioral intentions."],t.R)
B.LG=new A.Z(B.p,[73,5,"Rising","R","Rise",!1,"What do you want your life to feel like \u2014 not look like from the outside, but feel like from the inside \u2014 one year from now?","Start with the feeling. The life follows.","Emotional prediction of future states is far more motivationally powerful than outcome-based goal-setting."],t.R)
B.Mi=new A.Z(B.p,[74,5,"Rising","R","Rise",!1,"What is one pattern you identified in Phase 4 that you are now committing to actively interrupt? What does that commitment look like in practice this week?","A commitment without specifics is a wish.","Written commitments measurably increase follow-through versus private intention \u2014 the consistency principle."],t.R)
B.Mj=new A.Z(B.p,[75,5,"Rising","R","Rise",!1,"What does the version of you who is living in alignment with your values actually do differently \u2014 in the morning, in relationships, in how they speak to themselves?","Values without behavior are just aesthetics.","Behavioral specificity in values work is essential \u2014 vague values create vague behavior. Specific behavioral descriptions create actionable targets."],t.R)
B.MF=new A.Z(B.p,[76,5,"Rising","R","Rise",!1,"What is one relationship you want to invest more consciously in over the next 30 days? What specific actions would that investment look like?","Relationships grow in the direction you tend them.","Deliberate investment behaviors \u2014 not feelings \u2014 are the primary driver of relationship satisfaction and longevity."],t.R)
B.M3=new A.Z(B.p,[77,5,"Rising","R","Rise",!1,"What fear, if you moved through it rather than around it, would most change your life? What is the smallest possible step through it?","The smallest step through fear counts.","Graduated approach \u2014 not avoidance \u2014 is the only mechanism through which fear is extinguished. Emotional processing theory (Foa & Kozak)."],t.R)
B.MK=new A.Z(B.p,[78,5,"Rising","R","Reframe",!0,"Write your values as you understand them now \u2014 not as you were taught them, not as they sound impressive, but as they are actually lived in your best moments. Then write: where is the gap between these values and how you currently live?","The gap is not a failure. It is a direction.","Values clarification combined with values-behavior gap analysis is the foundational intervention in Acceptance and Commitment Therapy."],t.R)
B.LD=new A.Z(B.p,[79,5,"Rising","R","Rise",!1,"What would you start doing if you fully believed you deserved good things? Start there.","You deserve good things. This is not up for debate.","Deservingness beliefs are among the most clinically significant barriers to behavior change \u2014 they operate below conscious awareness and silently constrain action."],t.R)
B.M9=new A.Z(B.p,[80,5,"Rising","R","Rise",!1,"Who do you want to be in difficulty \u2014 when life is hard, when people disappoint you, when you are afraid? Describe that person in specific terms.","Character is what you practice before you need it.","Character-based identity goals produce more resilient behavior under stress than outcome-based goals."],t.R)
B.M7=new A.Z(B.p,[81,5,"Rising","R","Rise",!1,"What is something you have been wanting to say to someone that you have not said? What is stopping you? What would saying it make possible?","Unspoken things take up a great deal of space.","Emotional expression completion \u2014 finishing unexpressed emotional communications \u2014 is one of the most powerful interventions in Gestalt and emotion-focused therapy."],t.R)
B.M4=new A.Z(B.p,[82,5,"Rising","R","Rise",!1,"What does rest mean to you \u2014 not sleep, but genuine psychological restoration? Are you allowing yourself enough of it?","Rest is not a reward. It is a requirement.","Psychological detachment \u2014 not just inactivity \u2014 is the active ingredient in genuine rest. Most high-performing individuals are chronically under-recovered."],t.R)
B.Md=new A.Z(B.p,[83,5,"Rising","R","Rise",!1,"What is one thing you want to stop doing \u2014 not because someone told you to, but because you have now seen clearly that it doesn't serve who you are becoming?","Letting go is a form of self-respect.","Behavior cessation intentions are more effective when anchored in identity rather than consequences \u2014 identity-based habits research."],t.R)
B.LM=new A.Z(B.p,[84,5,"Rising","R","Reframe",!0,"What is the story you want to be able to tell about this season of your life \u2014 not what happened, but what you became because of what happened?","The story is still being written. You are the author.","Meaning-making narrative construction is the final stage in post-traumatic growth \u2014 the mechanism through which difficult experiences become sources of strength."],t.R)
B.Mb=new A.Z(B.p,[85,5,"Rising","R","Rise",!1,"What does self-respect look like for you \u2014 in action, in boundaries, in how you spend your time and who you allow into your life?","Self-respect is not a feeling. It is a set of decisions.","Self-respect is operationally defined in behavioral terms in DBT's FAST skills. Abstract self-respect without behavioral anchors remains aspirational."],t.R)
B.Lw=new A.Z(B.p,[86,5,"Rising","R","Rise",!1,"What have you forgiven yourself for during these 90 days? What still needs forgiving? Write what that forgiveness would actually sound like.","Forgiveness is not forgetting. It is choosing not to let it define you.","Self-forgiveness is a distinct psychological process from self-acceptance \u2014 it requires acknowledgment, remorse, and a genuine internal shift."],t.R)
B.M_=new A.Z(B.p,[87,5,"Rising","R","Rise",!1,"What does continuing this practice look like after Day 90? What specific form will your self-awareness work take going forward?","The practice does not end. It evolves.","Explicit planning for post-intervention continuation is the single strongest predictor of whether gains from reflective practice are sustained."],t.R)
B.LA=new A.Z(B.p,[88,5,"Rising","R","Rise",!1,"Write a letter to the person who started this journal on Day 1. What do you want them to know about what was coming?","You made it further than you thought you would.","Retrospective self-compassion letters consolidate the growth arc and create a powerful experiential marker of transformation."],t.R)
B.MJ=new A.Z(B.p,[89,5,"Rising","R","Rise",!1,"What is the single most important thing you know about yourself now that you did not know 89 days ago? Write it as a statement you will carry forward.","One true thing about yourself, held clearly, changes everything.","Distilling insight into a single clear formulation is the final stage of cognitive consolidation \u2014 it creates a portable, memorable anchor for changed behavior."],t.R)
B.Mc=new A.Z(B.p,[90,5,"Rising","R","Rise",!1,"What is your one next step \u2014 not your plan, not your goals, not your vision. Just the one honest next step from where you are standing right now.","One step. That is all. And then another.","Small, specific, self-chosen next steps produce higher rates of behavior change than any goal-setting framework \u2014 because they are owned, not assigned."],t.R)
B.IO=s([B.MN,B.Me,B.Ml,B.LS,B.ME,B.LH,B.Mt,B.Mr,B.My,B.Mm,B.MI,B.LY,B.MH,B.LU,B.LZ,B.Mf,B.MO,B.MP,B.Lz,B.MC,B.MA,B.Ms,B.M8,B.Ma,B.M2,B.Mx,B.Ly,B.MM,B.Lx,B.Mz,B.Mk,B.LC,B.M5,B.LE,B.Lu,B.Mg,B.LF,B.Mo,B.Mw,B.LK,B.MR,B.LT,B.LN,B.LR,B.Mp,B.MD,B.MG,B.LJ,B.Lt,B.Mu,B.LW,B.LX,B.LI,B.LB,B.MS,B.ML,B.LL,B.Lv,B.MQ,B.M0,B.M1,B.MT,B.M6,B.Mn,B.Mh,B.MB,B.LQ,B.LO,B.LP,B.Mv,B.LV,B.Mq,B.LG,B.Mi,B.Mj,B.MF,B.M3,B.MK,B.LD,B.M9,B.M7,B.M4,B.Md,B.LM,B.Mb,B.Lw,B.M_,B.LA,B.MJ,B.Mc],t.H7)
